1.2 Least Squares Regression

\[b_1 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \bar{x})(y_i - \bar{y})}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \bar{x})^2} = r\cdot \frac{s_y}{s_x}\]

\[b_0 = \bar{y} - b_1\cdot\bar{x}\]

\[e_i = y_i - \hat{y_i}\]

\[\hat{y_i} = b_0 + b_1\cdot x_i\]

DFP %>% 
  mutate(b1 = cor(x, y)*sd(y)/sd(x), b0 = mean(y)-b1*mean(x), yhat = b0 + b1*x, e = y - yhat) -> ans1
ans1

  1. Interpret the slope for mod2.

For every 1 square meter increase in area, there is an associated increase of, on average, 2,705 in totalprice.

  1. Create a 95% confidence interval for the mean price of apartments with 160 square meters.
predict(mod2, newdata = data.frame(area = 160), interval = "conf", level = 0.95) -> CI
CI
       fit      lwr      upr
1 473582.6 454031.6 493133.5

A 95% confidence interval for \(E(Y_h)\) is from 454,032 to 493,134.
